Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Qwaishun Montez Barnes in court with attorney Thomas Evangelos Harris.  Defendant Qwaishun Montez Barnes in custody.  Alexandria S. Carlson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties appeared via zoom.   Case in court for return on doctors report. Parties review and do not contest  Doctors Report dated 4/19/2022.  Court finds the defendant lacks substantial capacity to understand court proceedings or to assist in his own defense.  Court orders proceedings suspended. Court ordered defendant committed to the Department of Health and Family Services for Institutional Care in order to restore competency within the statutory time frame FORTHWITH. The Court further authorized DHS to administer medications or treatment to the defendant.  Defendant is REMANDED into the custody of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's Department for transportation to the designated facility.  Order of Commitment signed and filed.  At the request of counsels, Court agreed to move this hearing to Br 35 for next scheduled hearing.    mn  Review hearing scheduled for June 9, 2022 at 08:30 am.
